    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm studying for my structural mechanics exam. can u explain why we actually need to add steel rebar to concrete foundations? like why isnt the concrete itself enough to handle the loads? im a bit confused about the relationship between compressive and tensile strength here.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Concrete is exceptionally strong in compression, meaning it handles crushing forces very well, which is why it's excellent for foundations. However, concrete is very weak in tension, meaning it cracks easily when pulled apart. Adding steel rebar provides the necessary tensile strength to counteract those pulling forces, allowing the combined concrete-steel system to safely support bending and stretching loads. Essentially, steel takes the tension while concrete handles the compression, creating a material composite stronger than either alone.",
      "source": "target",
